hyp_text: The word urbanization comes from the Latin word urbs, meaning "city". The term "urban" may also refer to non-human habitats, such as very dense and crowded marine reefs or forest or ant hills. The adjective urban may be used to mean "related to the city", or it may be used in a wider sense to mean that "some thing relates to conditions prevalent in a town or city". For instance, urban apiculture, urban agriculture, and urban beekeeping are all forms of urban agriculture which occur within town or city limits. Living in a town or city can be culturally and economically different from living in a village or the countryside; dictionaries generally define urban as "of or relating to a city; characteristic of city life", a notion further developed by Wycliffe Hood. Urban areas are created and further developed by the process of urbanization. Measuring the extent of an urbanized area helps in analyzing population density and urban sprawl, and in determining urban and rural populations. Unlike an urban area, a metropolitan area includes not only the urban area, but also satellite cities plus intervening rural land that is socio-economically connected to the urban core city, typically by employment ties through commuting, with the urban core city being the primary labor market. In fact, urbanized areas agglomerate and grow as the core population/economic activity center within a larger metropolitan area or envelope. In the US, metropolitan statistical areas are defined as a cluster of counties with a core urban area. The counties containing the core urban area are known as the central counties of the MSA. The counties not containing the core urban area are known as outlying counties of the MSA. A city must have a population of 50,000 or more to qualify as an urban area in the EU; candidate countries must meet the same criteria by 2015. In Australia, urban areas are referred to as "urban centres" and are defined as population clusters of 1,000 or more people, with a density of at least 200/km2. According to the current urbanization projection trends, nearly 60% of the world's population will live in urban areas in 2030. The United Nations predicts that by 2050 over 70% of the world's population will be urban.
